{
  "text": "Sirtuin 3 (SIRT3) is a member of the silent information regulator 2 (Sir2) protein family. It is classified as class I SIRT together with SIRT1 and SIRT2, all of which exhibit a deacetylase activity in the presence of oxidized nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD + ) [CITATION_1] . SIRT3, SIRT4, and SIRT5 are all located in mitochondria, and SIRT3 is considered an enzyme of the mitochondrial matrix [CITATION_2] . In addition, SIRT3 catalyzes the deacetylation of two enzymes important for antioxidative protection, namely, SOD2 and isocitrate dehydrogenase 2 (IDH2). The activation of SOD2 and IDH2 mediates the antioxidant effect of SIRT3 [CITATION_3] . The neuroprotective action of SIRT3 was also reported in neurodegenerative disorders such as Alzheimer's disease [CITATION_4] and recently in an experimental model of PD [CITATION_5] . SIRT3 expression was also evident in PBMCs [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
